Objective:
The main objective of this lab is to understand the basics of VHDL (VHSIC Hardware Description Language) and 
to get familiar with an open-source simulation environment (GHDL and GTKWave). The lab also aims to learn how digital circuits can be designed, compiled, and simulated using VHDL, 
and how simulation tools are used to verify hardware behavior before physical implementation.

Theory:
VHDL (VHSIC Hardware Description Language) is a hardware description language used to model,
design, and simulate digital electronic systems. It allows engineers to describe the behavior
and structure of digital circuits such as logic gates, flip-flops, and complex processors. 
Unlike traditional programming languages, VHDL focuses on describing how hardware operates
in parallel rather than executing instructions sequentially.

A VHDL design typically consists of two main parts: the entity and the architecture. 
The entity defines the external interface of the circuit, including inputs and outputs, while the 
architecture describes the internal behavior or structure of the design. This separation helps in modular and reusable hardware design.

Simulation plays an important role in VHDL-based design because it allows verification of digital circuits before hardware implementation. 
In this lab, an open-source simulation environment such as GHDL is used to compile and run VHDL code, while GTKWave is used to visualize the output waveforms.
GHDL acts as a compiler and simulator, whereas GTKWave helps in analyzing signal transitions over time.

Using this environment, digital circuits can be tested efficiently, reducing design errors and improving understanding of hardware behavior.

A basic VHDL design is divided into two main parts:

Entity: Defines the external interface of the circuit (inputs and outputs).
Architecture: Describes the internal functionality or behavior of the circuit.

